Since $\angle ABC$ is trisected, $\angle ABP = \angle PBC.$  Since $\angle PBM$ bisects $\angle PBQ,$ $\angle ABQ = 2 \angle MBQ.$

Since $\angle ABP = \angle PBC,$
\[\angle ABQ = \angle ABP + \angle PBQ = \angle PBC + \angle PBQ.\]Since $BP$ and $BQ$ trisect $\angle ABC,$ $\angle PBC = \angle QBC.$  Hence,
\[\angle ABQ = \angle QBC + \angle PBQ.\]Since $\angle QBC + \angle CBQ = 180^\circ,$ $\angle QBC = 180^\circ - \angle CBQ.$  Therefore,
\[\angle ABQ = 180^\circ - \angle CBQ + \angle PBQ.\]Since $\angle MBQ$ bisects $\angle PBQ,$ $\angle CBQ = 2 \angle MBQ.$  Hence,
\[\angle ABQ = 180^\circ - 2 \angle MBQ + \angle PBQ.\]Finally, since $BP$ and $BQ$ trisect $\angle ABC,$ $\angle PBQ = \frac{1}{3} \angle ABC.$  Therefore,
\[\angle ABQ = 180^\circ - 2 \angle MBQ + \frac{1}{3} \angle ABC.\]Since $\angle ABC$ is trisected, $\angle ABC = 3 \angle PBC.$  Therefore,
\[\angle ABQ = 180^\circ - 2 \angle MBQ + \angle PBC.\]Since $\angle ABQ = 2 \angle MBQ,$ $\angle PBC = 3 \angle MBQ.$  Therefore,
\[\angle ABQ = 180^\circ - 2 \angle MBQ + 3 \angle MBQ = 180^\circ + \angle MBQ.\]Hence, $\angle MBQ$ is one-third of $\angle ABQ,$ so the ratio of the measure of $\angle MBQ$ to the measure of $\angle ABQ$ is $\boxed{\frac{1}{3}}.$

